&nbsp; The flight cancellations were occasioned by a strike by at least 500 employees outsourced by KQ through Career Direction Ltd (CDL) who began work boycott last Friday.PHOTO:COURTESY Kenya Airways (KQ) faces further turbulent times.Airline finally resumes cancelled flights but pilots insist strike still on from tomorrow Yesterday, the airline had cancelled five flights to various African countries as&nbsp; go-slow by its outsourced staff begun to weigh on its operations. And last evening, the airline announced that operations had returned to normalcy adding that 67 flights had taken off &ldquo;from the around the network as at 4pm Kenyan time.&rdquo; The flight cancellations were occasioned by a strike by at least 500 employees outsourced by KQ through Career Direction Ltd (CDL) who began work boycott last Friday. Flights 600 to Mombasa, 432 to Kilimajaro, 350 to Juba, 706 to Lusaka/Harare and 740 to Maputo were cancelled after their crew failed to report to work. Flight 782 to Livingston/Cape Town was also delayed, leaving hundreds of travelers stranded. READ MORE Kenya Airways cancels five flights &lsquo;due to staff shortage&rsquo; KQ obtains order to stop pilots from going on strike Come to rescue of Kenya Airways This month alone, the airline has cancelled or delayed flights twice, putting the &lsquo;Pride of Africa&rsquo; into more troubles. On October 2, KQ delayed flights at Moi International Airport and Jomo Kenyatta International Airport (JKIA). POOR REMUNERATION The contracted employees have decried poor remuneration, which they want addressed by the airline that has continued to post huge losses despite its efforts to cut down on its wage bill by outsourcing crew and other low cadre employees. &ldquo;Some of our outsourced staff including cabin crew have stayed away from work from Friday and we are working with their employer to resolve any issues they may have,&rdquo; KQ said in a statement. &ldquo;Despite our effort to solve the problem by combining several flights, we have made the difficult decision to cancel some as the safety of our guests is paramount,&rdquo; it added. GO TO PAGE 1 2 Next &raquo;